Below is a complete beginner-to-production-style guide to build an application, push the Docker image to Docker Hub, and deploy it to a Kubernetes cluster using Azure DevOps CI/CD — with separate staging and production environments.

I’ll keep it practical and easy to follow, while also applying production-level standards such as separate namespaces, secrets management, approvals, and safe deployments.

### What you will build

You will create this CI/CD flow:

Git Repository

Azure DevOps

Build Docker Image

Push to Docker Hub

Deploy to Staging

Deploy to Production

### Prerequisites

Before starting, make sure you have these accounts and tools:

| Item               | Purpose                           |
| ------------------ | --------------------------------- |
| GitHub             | Store your application code       |
| Docker Hub         | Store Docker images               |
| Azure DevOps       | Run CI/CD pipelines               |
| Kubernetes Cluster | Run your application              |
| kubectl            | Manage Kubernetes                 |
| Docker Desktop     | Build and test containers locally |

For learning, you can use Minikube or Docker Desktop Kubernetes. For production, use AKS or another managed Kubernetes service.

### Step 1: Create the application

We’ll use a simple Node.js Express app as the example.

### Create the project folder

Bash

```
mkdir my-app
cd my-app
```

### Initialize Node.js

Bash

```
npm init -y
npm install express
```

### Create app.js

Create a file named `app.js`:

JavaScript

```
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = process.env.PORT || 3000;

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello from Kubernetes CI/CD Pipeline!');
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`App running on port ${port}`);
});
```

### Update package.json

Replace the scripts section with:

JSON

```
"scripts": {
  "start": "node app.js"
}
```

### Step 2: Create the Dockerfile

In the project root, create a file named `Dockerfile`:

dockerfile

```
# Use official Node.js image
FROM node:20-alpine

# Create app directory
WORKDIR /usr/src/app

# Copy package files first for better caching
COPY package*.json ./

# Install dependencies
RUN npm install --only=production

# Copy application source code
COPY . .

# Expose application port
EXPOSE 3000

# Run the application
CMD ["npm", "start"]
```

### Create .dockerignore

```
node_modules
npm-debug.log
.git
.gitignore
```

This keeps the image small and production-ready.

### Step 3: Test locally with Docker

### Build the image

Bash

```
docker build -t my-app:v1 .
```

### Run the container

Bash

```
docker run -p 3000:3000 my-app:v1
```

Open your browser and go to:

```
http://localhost:3000
```

You should see:

```
Hello from Kubernetes CI/CD Pipeline!
```

### Step 4: Push the image to Docker Hub

### Create a Docker Hub repository

Go to Docker Hub and create a repository named `my-app`.

### Log in from your terminal

Bash

```
docker login
```

Enter your Docker Hub username and password or access token.

### Tag the image

Replace `your-dockerhub-username` with your actual Docker Hub username.

Bash

```
docker tag my-app:v1 your-dockerhub-username/my-app:v1
```

### Push the image

Bash

```
docker push your-dockerhub-username/my-app:v1
```

Your image is now stored in Docker Hub.

### Step 5: Create the Kubernetes cluster

For learning, start with Minikube.

### Start Minikube

Bash

```
minikube start --driver=docker
```

### Verify the cluster

Bash

```
kubectl get nodes
```

You should see one node in Ready state.

### Step 6: Create Kubernetes namespaces

Namespaces separate staging and production.

Bash

```
kubectl create namespace staging
kubectl create namespace production
```

Verify:

Bash

```
kubectl get namespaces
```

### Step 7: Create Kubernetes manifests

Create a folder named `k8s`.

Bash

```
mkdir k8s
```

### Deployment manifest

Create `k8s/deployment.yaml`:

YAML

```
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-app
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-app
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: my-app
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: my-app
        image: your-dockerhub-username/my-app:latest
        ports:
        - containerPort: 3000
        resources:
          requests:
            cpu: "100m"
            memory: "128Mi"
          limits:
            cpu: "500m"
            memory: "512Mi"
        livenessProbe:
          httpGet:
            path: /
            port: 3000
          initialDelaySeconds: 10
          periodSeconds: 10
        readinessProbe:
          httpGet:
            path: /
            port: 3000
          initialDelaySeconds: 5
          periodSeconds: 5
```

### Service manifest

Create `k8s/service.yaml`:

YAML

```
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-app-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: my-app
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 3000
  type: LoadBalancer
```

### Step 8: Deploy manually to test

### Deploy to staging

Bash

```
kubectl apply -f k8s/deployment.yaml -n staging
kubectl apply -f k8s/service.yaml -n staging
```

### Check pods

Bash

```
kubectl get pods -n staging
```

### Get service URL

Bash

```
minikube service my-app-service -n staging
```

If this works, your Kubernetes manifests are correct.

### Step 9: Set up Azure DevOps

### Create a project

* Go to Azure DevOps .

* Create a new organization if you do not have one.

* Create a new project named `my-app-ci-cd`.

### Connect your Git repository

* Push your application code to GitHub.

* In Azure DevOps, go to Pipelines → New Pipeline.

* Select GitHub as the source.

* Authorize Azure DevOps to access your GitHub repository.

### Step 10: Create service connections

### Docker Hub connection

* Go to Project Settings → Service connections.

* Click New service connection.

* Select Docker Registry.

* Choose Docker Hub.

* Enter your Docker Hub credentials.

* Name it `dockerhub-connection`.

### Kubernetes connection

* Create another service connection.

* Select Kubernetes.

* Choose your cluster type, such as AKS or generic Kubernetes.

* Provide the kubeconfig or connect directly if using AKS.

* Name it `k8s-connection`.

### Step 11: Create the Azure DevOps pipeline

Create a file named `azure-pipelines.yml` in the root of your repository.

YAML

```
trigger:
  branches:
    include:
      - main

variables:
  dockerRegistryServiceConnection: 'dockerhub-connection'
  kubernetesServiceConnection: 'k8s-connection'
  imageRepository: 'your-dockerhub-username/my-app'
  tag: '$(Build.BuildId)'

stages:
# Build Stage
- stage: Build
  displayName: Build and Push Docker Image
  jobs:
  - job: Build
    pool:
      vmImage: 'ubuntu-latest'
    steps:
    - task: Docker@2
      displayName: Build and Push Image
      inputs:
        command: buildAndPush
        repository: $(imageRepository)
        dockerfile: Dockerfile
        containerRegistry: $(dockerRegistryServiceConnection)
        tags: |
          $(tag)
          latest

# Deploy to Staging
- stage: Deploy_Staging
  displayName: Deploy to Staging
  dependsOn: Build
  jobs:
  - deployment: DeployStaging
    environment: 'staging'
    strategy:
      runOnce:
        deploy:
          steps:
          - task: KubernetesManifest@1
            inputs:
              action: deploy
              kubernetesServiceConnection: $(kubernetesServiceConnection)
              namespace: staging
              manifests: |
                k8s/deployment.yaml
                k8s/service.yaml
              containers: |
                $(imageRepository):$(tag)

# Deploy to Production
- stage: Deploy_Production
  displayName: Deploy to Production
  dependsOn: Deploy_Staging
  jobs:
  - deployment: DeployProduction
    environment: 'production'
    strategy:
      runOnce:
        deploy:
          steps:
          - task: KubernetesManifest@1
            inputs:
              action: deploy
              kubernetesServiceConnection: $(kubernetesServiceConnection)
              namespace: production
              manifests: |
                k8s/deployment.yaml
                k8s/service.yaml
              containers: |
                $(imageRepository):$(tag)
```

### Step 12: Configure environments and approvals

This is a production standard practice.

### Create environments

* In Azure DevOps, go to Pipelines → Environments.

* Create an environment named `staging`.

* Create another environment named `production`.

### Add approval for production

* Open the `production` environment.

* Go to Approvals and checks.

* Add an approval.

* Select yourself or another approver.

Now, every deployment to production will require manual approval.

### Step 13: Push code and run the pipeline

### Commit your code

Bash

```
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
```

### Push to GitHub

Bash

```
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/my-app.git
git push -u origin main
```

Azure DevOps will automatically trigger the pipeline.

### Step 14: Verify the deployment

### Check staging

Bash

```
kubectl get pods -n staging
kubectl get svc -n staging
```

### Check production

Bash

```
kubectl get pods -n production
kubectl get svc -n production
```

### Production-level standards you should follow

| Standard                   | Why it matters                                        |
| -------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| Separate namespaces        | Isolates staging and production                       |
| Resource limits            | Prevents one app from consuming all cluster resources |
| Liveness probes            | Restarts unhealthy containers                         |
| Readiness probes           | Ensures traffic only goes to healthy pods             |
| Image tagging              | Use unique build IDs instead of only latest           |
| Secrets                    | Store passwords in Kubernetes Secrets, not in YAML    |
| Manual production approval | Prevents accidental deployments                       |
| Monitoring                 | Use Prometheus, Grafana, or Azure Monitor             |

### Recommended project structure

```
my-app/
│
├── app.js
├── package.json
├── Dockerfile
├── .dockerignore
├── azure-pipelines.yml
└── k8s/
    ├── deployment.yaml
    └── service.yaml
```

### What happens after everything is set up

* You push code to the `main` branch.

* Azure DevOps builds the Docker image.

* The image is pushed to Docker Hub.

* The app is deployed automatically to `staging`.

* You test the staging environment.

* You approve the deployment.

* The app is deployed to `production`.

This is a real-world CI/CD pipeline that follows many production best practices and is suitable for a junior-to-mid-level DevOps engineer to demonstrate in interviews or on a portfolio.

